{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:17:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:17:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.17,0.05,0.5,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9822"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"2900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45040"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal female is admitted to hospital with a two-month history of joint pain and fatigue. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has oral ulcers, non-scarring alopecia and synovitis in the small joints in both hands. Investigations reveal multiple abnormalities including positive antinuclear antibodies with a titre of 1:640 and autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be LEAST helpful in identifying renal involvement in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal biopsy","24-hour urine collection","Urine albumin-creatinine ratio","Renal doppler ultrasound","Urine microscopy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), including oral ulcers, non-scarring alopecia, synovitis, positive ANA, and autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. Lupus nephritis is a common and serious manifestation of SLE that requires early identification and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing and classifying lupus nephritis. It provides crucial information about the histological subtype of lupus nephritis and severity of kidney involvement, which guides treatment decisions and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine collection\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine albumin-creatinine ratio\u003C/strong\u003E are both valid methods for quantifying proteinuria, which is a key marker (and the most common abnormality) seen in lupus nephritis. Whilst 24-hour urine collection provides a more accurate quantification of proteinuria, the collection process is not always practical, hence a spot urine albumin-creatinine ratio can provide a quick and reasonable accurate measure of proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is essential as it can reveal active urinary sediment, including dysmorphic red blood cells, which is an indicator of active lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the least helpful investigation for identifying lupus nephritis. While it may show kidney size and exclude obstruction, it does not provide specific information about lupus nephritis activity or classification. Changes in renal blood flow are neither sensitive nor specific for lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen screening for lupus nephritis, it is important to assess for renal impairment (serum creatinine and estimated glomerular filtration rate), proteinuria (either by spot ratio test or 24hour urine collection) and microscopic haematuria (urine microscopy). If clinical suspicion is combined with any of the above abnormalities, strong consideration should be given to renal biopsy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith regards to the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population, there exists an increased incidence of SLE compared to non-Indigenous people. There also exists an increased rate of lupus nephritis as a manifestation of SLE, as well as increased rates of progression to end-stage kidney disease in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people with lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When screening for lupus nephritis, it is important to assess for renal impairment, proteinuria and microscopic haematuria.","If clinical suspicion is combined with any of the above abnormalities, strong consideration should be given to renal biopsy.","There are higher rates of SLE and lupus nephritis in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population."],"references":["Musa R, Brent LH, Qurie A. Lupus Nephritis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499817/","Eades LE et al. Systemic lupus erythematosus in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in Australia: addressing disparities and barriers to optimising patient care. The Lancet Rheumatology. Volume 6, Issue 10, e713 - e726. Available at: 10.1016/S2665-9913(24)00095-X"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:17:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:17:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9822"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96800"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the e